Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 60

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Extra Observations about the restaurant names column:

  • A thorough observation of the restaurant list lets us know there are indeed problems and opportunities hidden in this field of data:

a) Some names seem to be duplicated with "alternative" spellings, like 'Blue Ribbon Brooklyn' and 'Blue Ribbon Fried Chicken'; 'Blue Ribbon Sushi', 'Blue Ribbon Sushi Bar & Grill', and 'Blue Ribbon Sushi Izakaya' (In fact the word "izakaya" is japanese that roughly translates as "bar" or "pub", so the last 3 names might very well be the same business); "Vanessa's Dumpling House" and "Vanessa's Dumplings", among others. However, before discarding, grouping, or renaming the apparent duplicates a little extra research is required. For the scope of this project, this list will not be modified.

b) There might be special character issues with some names (maybe chinese and spanish).

c) Some names include commentary like "(closed)" which could be put in a separate column and enrich the data analysis with extra insights, like as follows:

In [8]:
df['Closed'] = [1 if df['restaurant_name'][idx].find('closed')!=-1 else 0 for idx in range(df.shape[0])] # new column with a dummy variable (1 = 'closed')

closed_orders = df[df['Closed']==1].shape[0] # Count of orders from "closed" restaurants

pct_cl_od = round(closed_orders/df.shape[0]*100,2) # % of orders from "closed" restaurants

closed_rest_str = ", ".join(df[df['Closed']==1]['restaurant_name'].unique()) # if more than one, they will show up as a string separated by commas.

print (f'{closed_orders} orders ({pct_cl_od}%) are from closed restaurants: {closed_rest_str}')

13 orders (0.68%) are from closed restaurants: Empanada Mama (closed)

Luckily the number of rows with this particular issue are very few, and won't affect the analysis in a significant way.

There's also an "archived" for a repeated restaurant name which will be ignored for lack of better information.

3. Ratings:

In [11]:
df['rating'].unique()
Out[11]:
array(['Not given', '5', '3', '4'], dtype=object)

We can see (again) that there are orders where no rating was given. Attributing a rating value to these cases could distort the analysis, but having a string value instead of a null value doesn't allow us to figure out the ratings distribution or statistical information for rated orders. The proposed solution is the following, where the original column will be conserved for categorical analysis purposes:

In [12]:
# Every 'Not Given' value in the 'rating' column is turned into a null value.
# The result is saved in a new column to avoid losing data.
df['rating_value'] = df['rating'].replace(['Not given'],np.nan)
df['rating_value'] = df['rating_value'].astype(float)

# The 'object' type original column needs to be categorized properly to get a tidier analysis:
rat_cat = ['Not given', '3', '4', '5']
df.rating = pd.Categorical(df.rating, ordered=True, categories=rat_cat)

  • The most ordered cuisine type is American.
  • A majority of orders are placed on weekends.

Restaurant Names (restaurant_name):¶

Univariate analysis for the column 'restaurant_name', means analyzing the number of orders per restaurant. As there are too many for a clean analysis, aggregating by restaurant and filtering the top 80% of orders, Pareto-style seems like a good practice.

In [18]:
# Building an auxiliary Data Frame to study the performance of each restaurant
rest_lst = df['restaurant_name'].unique()
orders_rest = [df[df['restaurant_name']==rest]['order_id'].count() for rest in rest_lst]
agg_rest = pd.DataFrame({'restaurant': rest_lst, 'orders': orders_rest})

agg_rest = agg_rest.sort_values(by = 'orders', ascending = False).reset_index() # sorting from highest to lowest order qty
agg_rest.drop('index', axis=1, inplace=True) # dropping the old index
agg_rest['orders'] = agg_rest['orders'].astype(int)

# Filling new columns to help determine normalized performance and accumulated % of orders (to filter the top 80% later)
agg_rest['pct'] = np.zeros(len(rest_lst))
agg_rest['pct_ac'] = np.zeros(len(rest_lst)) # accumulated % of orders

par_tot = 0

for indx in range(len(rest_lst)):
    par_tot += agg_rest.loc[indx,'orders']
    agg_rest.loc[indx,'pct'] = agg_rest.loc[indx,'orders'] / df.shape[0] * 100
    agg_rest.loc[indx,'pct_ac'] = par_tot / df.shape[0] * 100
agg_rest[agg_rest['pct_ac']<=80] # selection of top restaurants by quantity of orders, for 80% of orders.

The boxplot allows to observe that most cuisine types have similar ranges for their cost orders, with some nuances:

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [57]:
# a function seems to be the simplest way to calculate the amount (fee) FoodHub charges the restaurants for each order
def fee (cost):
    if cost > 20:
        return cost * 0.25
    elif cost > 5:
        return cost * 0.15
    else:
        return 0

df['fee'] = [fee(df.loc[x,'cost_of_the_order']) for x in range(df.shape[0])]
total_fee = df['fee'].sum()
print(f'The net revenue generated by FoodHub from the orders listed in the data set is {round(total_fee, 2)} dollars.')
mean_pc_ord = total_fee / df.cost_of_the_order.sum()
print(f'\nOn average, that means about {round(total_fee/df.shape[0], 2)} dollars per order, or {round(mean_pc_ord*100, 1)}% of the mean order cost.')

The net revenue generated by FoodHub from the orders listed in the data set is 6166.3 dollars.

On average, that means about 3.25 dollars per order, or 19.7% of the mean order cost.

Observations:¶

It's interesting that FoodHub earns about 20% of the cost of the orders on average. With more research about the effects of the fee structure on order amounts and quantities, an optimization algorithm could be used to verify if the fee structure is indeed optimal.

Question 15: The company wants to analyze the total time required to deliver the food. What percentage of orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered from the time the order is placed? (The food has to be prepared and then delivered.) [2 marks]¶

In [58]:
# Write the code here
df['wait_time'] = df['food_preparation_time'] + df['delivery_time']

# number of orders that mtch the condition, also on weekends as additional info
over_60 = df[df['wait_time'] > 60].shape[0]
over_60_wend = df[(df['wait_time'] > 60) & (df['day_of_the_week']=='Weekend')].shape[0]

# percent indicators
pc_over_60 = over_60/df.shape[0]
pc_over_60_wday = over_60_wend/df[df['day_of_the_week']=='Weekday'].shape[0]

print(f'{round(pc_over_60*100, 1)}% of orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered.')
print(f'\nThe proportion for week days is {round(pc_over_60_wday*100, 1)}%')

10.5% of orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered.

The proportion for week days is 14.8%

Observations:¶

For about 11% of orders the customer has to wait more than 60 minutes. Only considering week days, the proportion goes up to almost 15%.

One hour of waiting could be very well a psychological boundary that discourages orders. There is little information about what drives preparation times, but delivery times are clearly the source of the difference between weekends and week days in terms of waiting time.

Question 16: The company wants to analyze the delivery time of the orders on weekdays and weekends. How does the mean delivery time vary during weekdays and weekends? [2 marks]¶

In [59]:
# averages for delivery time, on weekdays and weekends
wday_deltime_avg = df[df['day_of_the_week']=='Weekday']['delivery_time'].mean()
wend_deltime_avg = df[df['day_of_the_week']=='Weekend']['delivery_time'].mean()

print(f'Average delivery time on weekends is about {round(wend_deltime_avg, 1)} minutes,',
      f'while on weekdays is {round(wday_deltime_avg, 1)} minutes.', 
      f'Thats a {round((wday_deltime_avg/wend_deltime_avg-1)*100, 1)}% increase.')

Average delivery time on weekends is about 22.5 minutes, while on weekdays is 28.3 minutes. Thats a 26.1% increase.

Observations:¶

As seen in the multivariate analysis, there's a substantial increase of delivery times on week days, which can be caused by traffic or less availability of delivery people. Geographical location of the customers (which is unknown) could also influence this. Maybe the business district is farther from the restaurants on average and most week day orders are lunch orders from offices? Detailed date-time and geographical information could help answer this question.

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]¶

Conclusions:¶

After the analysis of a dataset containing 1,898 orders placed through FoodHub, the following insights can be drawn:

  • The restaurants list might need some cleaning of repeated and closed locals. More research is needed to take advantage of the opportunities hidden in this list
  • 75% of customers placed 2 orders or less, while some "outlier" customers placed 4 to 13 orders each.
  • 80% of orders were taken by only 42 restaurants out of 178, with the top 4 restaurants having more than 90 orders each. On the other hand, half the restaurants took only 3 orders each or less. The top 5 restaurants are: Shake Shack, The Meatball Shop, Blue Ribbon Sushi, Blue Ribbon Fried Chicken, and Parm.
  • Most orders (83%) are concentrated in a few cuisine types: American (31%), Japanese (25%), Italian (16%) and Chinese (11%).
  • Almost three-quarters of the orders are placed on weekends, following almost the same order of preference in regards to cuisine types.
  • The cost of orders varies between 4.47 to 35.41 dollars. Half of the orders cost less than 14 dollars. The top 4 cuisine types (American, Japanese, Italian and Chinese) have slightly lower median order costs than the following 3 (Mexican, Indian, Middle-Eastern). Thai and French median order costs are noticeably higher, while Korean and Vietnamese orders seem to be cheaper.
  • Food preparation time varies between 20 and 35 minutes, with an average of about 27 minutes. The distribution of this variable is almost uniform, with little difference between days of the week or cuisine types.
  • Delivery times vary between 15 and 33 minutes. There's a substantial (26%) increase of delivery times on week days, which can be caused by traffic, less availability of delivery people, or geographical considerations. Delivery time follows an almost uniform distribution for both weekends and week days (but logically not for the whole number of orders).
  • For about 11% of the orders the customer has to wait more than 60 minutes for their order. On week days, it’s almost 15% (clearly lower for weekends). One hour of wait time could be very well a psychological boundary that discourages orders and could be acted upon.
  • Ratings information doesn’t help much to understand the quality of the customer experience, because of the large number of orders without a rating given (almost 40%). Also, the ratings score is slanted towards “perfect” scores, with about half the given ratings being top scores. Maybe customers just find the ratings interface annoying. The limited analysis that was possible to undertake suggests that Indian and Southern cuisines have higher mean ratings than the rest. Thai and French cuisines, among others, could have lower mean rating scores, but the low quantity and quality of the data doesn't allow for solid conclusions.
  • Promotional offers could incentivize restaurants to ask customers for their rating score, improving the quality of the data gathering
  • The cuisine types with the most quantity of restaurants are American, Japanes and Italian, which explains a lot about their relative higher order quantities.
  • Japanese, American and Chinese restaurants have the highest turnover in terms of orders per restaurant. Thai, Korean, Spanish and Vietnamese restaurants apparently have very low turnovers. Indian restaurants seem to have potential, they got good average ratings, and they seem to have relatively low orders per restaurant.
  • FoodHub earned 6,166.3 dollars from the orders listed in the dataset, that’s about 20% of the cost of the orders on average, or 3.25 dollars per order.
  • No significant correlation was detected in this dataset between any of the numerical variables: order cost, preparation time, delivery time or ratings.

Recommendations:¶

  • Suggest to restaurants, as a way to increase sales on week days, to reduce preparation times and thus, waiting times, by proposing weekday simplified menus with convenient lunch combos for businesses, to streamline their kitchens. The increased sales could help restaurants’ use of idle capacity and improve FoodHub’s earnings.
  • Help restaurants in the Mexican, Indian and Mediterranean cuisines (among others with potential) increase their sales through special promotions and events, like for example “Curry Friday Night” as a way to introduce more exotic flavors to customers. Suggest they reduce their average prices a little, maybe creating standardized combos and simplifying their menus, focusing on signature dishes.
  • The high proportion of orders not rated, and the distribution of the ratings doesn't help understand the customer experience nor take any action about it. Maybe the rating scale could be better defined for the customer so they add more nuances to their ratings and opt less frequently for max ratings unless the experience was remarkable.Some rating interfaces often ask for written details or ask extra questions when the rating is not "perfect". That could discourage an honest appraisal of the experience. Finally, some kind of incentive for giving a rating every time could be figured out, like (as examples) loyalty coupons and periodic free meal lottos. Persevering in promotional advertising offers could incentivize restaurants to help ask customers for their rating score, improving the quality of the data gathering.
  • The most important thing is to protect and reward success, as a big proportion of orders, and thus FoodHub’s income, is concentrated in just a few restaurants. Keep regular communication with top restaurants and get constant feedback about the delivery service, the ordering app, coupons, promotional material, advertising, and other concerns.

Suggested further research and analysis:¶

  • Adding detailed date/time information to the orders could bring new and important insights to the analysis, like identifying orders placed during rush hours. This could improve the prediction of total waiting times (after a ML algorythm is run, which is outside the scope of this analysis).
  • Also, adding location information of restaurants and customers could help get a better understanding of geographical differences between weekend and weekday orders, and delivery times.
  • Update and clean the restaurant list if needed. Get more information about common franchises, locals with the same owner, same brand with multiple locations, etc.
  • With more research about the effects of the fee structure on order amounts and quantities, an optimization algorithm could be used to search for ways to improve the fee structure, increasing earnings.
